The paper discusses the application of kernel-based multi-task learning techniques to forecast the demand of electricity in multiple nodes of a distribution network. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of output kernel learning techniques, which are a type of kernel-based learning, indicating that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also deals with modeling complex seasonal effects and learning and exploiting correlations between multiple demand profiles, which are topics that fall under the Statistical Learning (cs.SI) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves the use of predictive models, which suggests that it may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
